attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): habitational name from a minor place of this name, for example Cockcroft in Rishworth or Cock Croft in Bingley, both in Yorkshire. They are named with Old English <i>cocc</i> ‘rooster’ + <i>croft</i> ‘paddock, smallholding’. In some cases it may be a topographic name with the same meaning."],"variants":[{"name":"Cockroft","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Cockcroft  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Cockcroft was born in 1590, in London, Sumner, Kansas, United States, his father, Caleb Cockcroft, was 20 and his mother, Elizabeth Sydenham, was 11587. He married Mary Wade about 1610, in Netherlands. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1630, in Cleveland, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1590–1630":"1590–1630","1589–Female":"1589–Surnud","1605–1677":"1605–1677","1610–1689":"1610–1689","1570–1645":"1570–1645","1575–1680":"1575–1680","1645":"1645","1689":"1689","1677":"1677","1589":"1589","1610":"1610","1630":"1630","1575":"1575","about 1610":"umbes 1610","1680":"1680","1570":"1570","1590":"1590","16